<TITLE> Serbia May election key to visa abolition: EU </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BRUSSELS, April 3 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The outcome of Serbia's parliamentary election in May will determine whether the European Union's conditions for visa-free travel are met, the EU's Enlargement Commissioner said. Olli Rehn declined to endorse a party in the election but said it was up to Serbs to decide if they wanted to move ahead. Polls show the election will be a neck-and-neck race between the pro-Western Democratic Party and the nationalist Radicals. "We don't have a vote in the elections of Serbia," he told reporters after meeting Serbian parliament speaker Oliver Dulic. "The parliamentary elections are thus crucial in order to facilitate such a parliamentary majority which will be able to and willing to deliver as regards conditions necessary to visa-free travel." Last month the EU laid out incentives on visas, education and transport in an effort to boost its image and help the pro-Western camp ahead of the election. Nationalist and anti-Western feeling has been boosted in Serbia by the Western-backed secession of Albanian-majority Kosovo, a province under United Nations stewardship since 1999. The Democratic Party has said it will never accept the secession of Kosovo but insists on EU membership. It says the two issues are not linked. The Radicals, Serbia's biggest party, favour joining the EU but only if the bloc respects Serbia's borders, effectively asking Brussels to choose between wooing Serbia and supporting Kosovo's independen
